    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1978-12-12T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1978-12-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="165"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d165">
                <head>165. Report of a Policy Review Committee Meeting<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d165fn1">Source: Carter Library, National Security Affairs, Staff
                        Material, Far East, <persName corresp="#p_OM_2">Oksenberg</persName> Subject
                        File, Box 45, Meetings: 12/6–12/78. Secret. <persName corresp="#p_IKF_1"
                            >Inderfurth</persName> sent this report to <persName corresp="#p_OM_2"
                            >Oksenberg</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_HB_1"
                            >Huberman</persName> under a December 13 covering memorandum that
                        stated, “Attached is the report which Zbig gave the President yesterday on
                        the above meeting. Please note the President’s ‘OK’ and follow up.” The
                        Summary of Conclusions of the December 12 <gloss target="#t_PRC_1"
                            >PRC</gloss> meeting is <ref target="#d164">Document 164</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1978-12-12T16:00:00-05:00"
                            notBefore="1978-12-12T00:00:00-05:00" when="1978-12-12">undated</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">
                    <gloss target="#t_PRC_1">PRC</gloss> on China Science and Technology</p>
                <p>Yesterday’s <gloss target="#t_PRC_1">PRC</gloss> on China surveyed our entire
                        <gloss target="#t_SnT_1">S&amp;T</gloss> relationship, but decisions were
                    necessary only on the communications satellite. There was unanimous interagency
                    agreement to slightly upgrade the quality of the satellite we are prepared to
                    offer Peking.<note n="2" xml:id="d165fn2">Carter made a checkmark in the margin
                        next to this paragraph.</note> Agreement was also reached to tie in our
                    willingness to provide and launch the satellite with Chinese agreement to
                    purchase ground stations from us rather than would-be Western European or
                    Japanese competitors. Decisions were also reached to continue to minimize the
                    technology to be transferred in the sale.</p>
                <p>The total package of two satellites, launching, and ground stations is on the
                    order of half a billion dollars and would be extremely important to U.S.
                        industry.<note n="3" xml:id="d165fn3">Carter wrote what appears to be “ok”
                        in the margin next to this paragraph.</note> The meeting also touched on the
                    evolving <gloss target="#t_SnT_1">S&amp;T</gloss> exchange program involving
                        <gloss target="#t_ICA_1">ICA</gloss>, NSF, Energy, and Agriculture, all of
                    which are moving according to the plan you have previously approved.</p>
            </div>
